  "opinion": "As a retired man from Philadelphia who spent most of his life in the shadow of the city’s bustling academic institutions, I’ve observed the gender gap in science through the lens of my own experiences and the stories of my neighbors. The gap isn’t just about fewer women in labs or lecture halls—it’s deeper, more insidious. It’s the subtle discouragement a young girl might feel when her teacher says, 'Science is for boys,' or the quiet resignation of a woman who’s been told her ideas are 'too emotional' to be taken seriously. I’ve seen this in my community, where the few women I know who pursue STEM fields often face a double burden: proving their competence while navigating a culture that still views science as a male domain. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do so matters. We must move beyond tokenism and create systems that value diverse perspectives from the start. For me, this means supporting mentorship programs that pair young girls with female scientists in the same fields they’re studying, not just as 'role models' but as peers who share their struggles and triumphs. It also means challenging the language we use in classrooms—replacing phrases like 'boys will be boys' with discussions about how collaboration and empathy are strengths in science. As a Buddhist, I believe in the interconnectedness of all beings, so I see the gender gap as a symptom of a larger disconnection in how we teach and value knowledge. We must cultivate environments where curiosity is nurtured without gender constraints. The solution isn’t just policy changes but a cultural shift—one that starts in the classrooms of my grandchildren and continues through the stories we tell about who belongs in science.",
